# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arecoline
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] 3C-PEP is one of the most potent dopamine transporter (DAT) ligands reported to date.
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] It is highly selective for the dopamine transporter (dissociation constant Ki = 0.04 nM) with relatively low affinity for the closely related norepinephrine transporter (NET, Ki = 1107 nM ) and the serotonin transporter (SERT, Ki = 802 nM).
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] In addition, the compound has lower (or no) affinity for the PCP/NMDA receptor (Ki > 10000 nM), D2-like receptors (Ki = 327 nM), serotonin 5-HT2 receptors (Ki = 53 nM), and opioid receptors (Ki > 10000 nM).
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] With a DAT dissociation constant Ki of 0.04 nM, 3C-PEP is one of the most potent dopamine transporter ligands described to date in the literature.
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] In comparison, cocaine which is a prototypical DAT ligand and reuptake inhibitor has a dissociation constant Ki of 435 nm thus making 3C-PEP about 10,000 times more potent than cocaine as a dopamine transporter inhibitor *in vitro*.
[src:arecoline/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] 3C-PEP is not scheduled under the Controlled Drugs and Substances Act.
[src:arecoline/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] It has high lipophilicity, allowing it to penetrate the blood-brain barrier without hindrance, which was accompanied by high, uniform uptake by the brain (approximately 8% of the administered dose), similar to that observed for the structurally related analogue [11C]methamphetamine.
[src:arecoline/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] The ephedrine (1R,2S) isomer is three times more effective than the pseudoephedrine (1S,2S) isomer, it is a metabolically stable compound.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] 18-MC was originally developed by Savant HWP and later acquired by MindMed in 2019 for development as a treatment for opioid use disorder.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] A Phase 1 trial in healthy volunteers was completed in 2022 with favorable safety and tolerability.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] Due to strategic reprioritization, MindMed discontinued active development of MM-110 in 2023 and has been seeking non-dilutive funding or partners to potentially restart the program; as of 2025 the program remains shelved.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] A separate Phase 2 trial in Brazil for cutaneous leishmaniasis (initiated 2017) has unknown status with no published results.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] The sites of action in the brain include the medial habenula, interpeduncular nucleus, dorsolateral tegmentum and basolateral amygdala.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] (±)-18-MC competitively inhibits α9α10 nAChRs with potencies higher than that at α3β4 and α4β2 nAChRs and directly blocks CaV2.2.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] A number of derivatives of 18-MC have been developed, with several of them being superior to 18-MC itself, the methoxyethyl congener ME-18-MC being more potent than 18-MC with similar efficacy, and the methylamino analogue 18-MAC being more effective than 18-MC with around the same potency.
[src:arecoline/18-methoxycoronaridine] These compounds were also found to act as selective α3β4 nicotinic acetylcholine antagonists, with little or no effect on NMDA receptors.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] It is a phenyltropane derivative that binds to the dopamine transporter with approximately 20 times the affinity of cocaine.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] However, it produces relatively mild stimulant effects, with a slow onset and a long duration of action.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] These characteristics make it a potential candidate for the treatment of cocaine addiction, as a possible substitute drug, analogous to the use of methadone for treating heroin dependence.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] RTI-336 fully substitutes for cocaine in addicted monkeys and supports self-administration, and significantly reduces rates of cocaine use, especially when combined with SSRIs.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] Research is ongoing to determine whether it could be a viable substitute drug in human cocaine addicts.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] RTI-336 and RTI-177 exhibited lower reinforcing strength than cocaine in nonhuman primates, indicating reduced abuse liability and supporting their viability as pharmacotherapies for addiction.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] Chronic RTI-336 administration in rhesus monkeys altered motor activity and sleep patterns but did not cause adverse hormonal changes, suggesting a relatively safe profile for long-term therapeutic use.
[src:arecoline/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] A dosage of up to 20mg has been tolerated in healthy males.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Side effects of arecoline include hypersalivation, hypotension, vertigo, miosis, tremor, and bradycardia, among others.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Other adverse effects can include extrapyramidal syndrome and seizures.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Addiction and dependence can occur, with withdrawal symptoms including mood swings, anxiety, irritability, and insomnia.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Rarely, psychosis can occur during withdrawal in heavy users.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Areca nut use, the primary method of consuming arecoline, is highly associated with oral disease and oral cancer.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Overdose of arecoline can be treated with antimuscarinic drugs like atropine or scopolamine.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The drug acts as a non-selective partial agonist of muscarinic and nicotinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The major metabolite of arecoline, arecaidine, is a GABA reuptake inhibitor.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The subjective effects of arecoline appear to be mediated by muscarinic acetylcholine receptors and not by nicotinic acetylcholine receptors based on animal studies.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] However, its mechanism of action is still yet to be fully understood and other activities have also been described.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The stimulant and addictive effects of arecoline are thought to be due to increased dopaminergic neurotransmission in the mesolimbic pathway of the brain.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] In terms of chemical structure, arecoline is closely related to nicotinic acid.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The use of arecoline, in the form of areca nuts, dates back several thousand years, including in Thailand, China, and Polynesia.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline was first isolated in 1888 by Ernst Jahns and its synthesis was first proposed in 1891, with its chemical structure confirmed in 1907.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The first complete synthesis was reported by Fritz Chemnitius at Jena University (Germany) in 1926.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline, in the form of areca nuts, is used by more than 600 million people worldwide (~10–20% of the global population), and is the fourth most commonly used psychoactive drug in the world after alcohol, nicotine, and caffeine.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Despite globalization, arecoline is unusual among recreational drugs in that its use is still predominantly confined to Asia, though its use has been increasing and spreading in part due to the Internet.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Chewing areca nuts is said to be as familiar to various Asian peoples as chewing gum is to Americans.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The countries in which areca nut production are highest include India, China, Myanmar, Malaysia, Indonesia, and Bangladesh.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline and areca nut sale and consumption are not generally controlled throughout the world, with a few exceptions.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] In many Asian cultures, the areca nut is chewed along with betel leaf to obtain a stimulating effect.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline has been used medicinally as an antihelmintic (a drug against parasitic worms).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline has been used in traditional medicine in Asia for thousands of years.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The LD50 of arecoline is 100 mg/kg, when administered subcutaneously in mice.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The minimum lethal dose (MLD) values of arecoline in mice, dogs, and horses is 100 mg/kg, 5 mg/kg and 1.4 mg/kg respectively.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Current science is confident that areca nut chewing is carcinogenic.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Research suggests this is probably at least partly because of arecoline itself, although it could also be from the other constituents of the nut as well, some of which are precursors to nitrosamines that form in the mouth during chewing.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The toxicity of arecoline can be partially mitigated by vitamins C and E in mice.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is "obviously cytotoxic" to cultures of hepatocytes, bone marrow cells, lymphocytes, neuronal cell, myoblasts and endothelial cells.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline generates excessive reactive oxygen species (ROS) in a number of cell types, including oral epithelial cells and neuronal cells.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] In adult mice, arecoline is toxic to the testes and liver via ROS generation.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is also genotoxic, being able to induce DNA damage and mutation in several cell cultures.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Mice chronically exposed to arecoline show relaxation of their chromatin structure.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is the primary active ingredient responsible for the central nervous system effects of the areca nut.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline has been compared to nicotine; however, nicotine agonizes nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, whereas arecoline is primarily a partial agonist of muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, leading to its parasympathetic effects.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] In frogs, arecoline also acts as an antagonist (or very weak partial agonist) at α4 and α6-containing nicotinic acetylcholine receptors and as a silent antagonist at α7 nicotinic receptors, which may account for its anti-inflammatory activity.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline also inhibits AMPK through generation of ROS in several types of cells.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] AN (Areca Nut) is a vasodilator mainly due to the presence of arecoline.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It also has anti-thrombosis and anti-atherogenic effects by increasing plasma nitric oxide, eNos, and mRNA expression and decreasing IL-8 along with other downregulations.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It increases the level of testosterone by stimulating Leydig's cells as well as levels of FSH and LH.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It also activates HPA axis and stimulates CRH release.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It prevents the dysfunction of B cells of the pancreas from high fructose intake.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline has the ability to stimulate the digestive system through the activation of muscarinic receptors.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Areca nut water extract could increase the contractions of gastric smooth muscle and muscle strips of the duodenum, ileum, and colon significantly.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] This activity could be caused by arecoline.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is metabolized by both kidneys and liver.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Currently, 11 metabolites of arecoline are documented among which *N*-methylnipecotic acid was found to be a major metabolite of both arecoline and arecaidine.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Lime, which is traditionally mixed to crushed areca nuts prior to consumption, is said to hydrolyse almost all arecoline to arecaidine, a GABA reuptake inhibitor.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecaidine is also formed during liver metabolism of arecoline in rats.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is very efficiently absorbed through oral musoca, with 85% bioavailbility.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Maximum plasma concentration is reached within 3 minutes.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Orally ingested arecoline is extensively metabolized in rats, with the vast majority of the dose being converted to arecaidine and arecoline *N*-oxide.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is a colorless odorless oily liquid.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It is a base, and its conjugate acid has a pKa ~ 6.8.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is volatile in steam, miscible with most organic solvents and water, but extractable from water by ether in presence of dissolved salts.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Being basic, arecoline forms salts with acids.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The salts are crystalline, but usually deliquescent: the hydrochloride, arecoline•HCl, forms needles, m.p.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] 158 °C; the hydrobromide, arecoline•HBr, forms slender prisms, mp.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] 177–179 °C from hot methanol; the aurichloride, arecoline•HAuCl4, is an oil, but the platinichloride, arecoline2•H2PtCl6, mp.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] 176 °C, crystallizes from water in orange-red rhombohedrons.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The methiodide forms glancing prisms, mp.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The double Michael reaction between methyl acrylate [96-33-3] (**1**) and aqueous methylamine (**2**) gave N,N-Bis(-methoxycarbonylethyl)methylamine [105-71-5] (**3**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] The reduction of the ketone group with sodium borohydride gave N-Methyl-3-carbomethoxy-4-hydroxypiperidine, PC3029557 (**5**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Reaction with methanesulfonyl chloride followed by addition of hydrobromic acid completed the synthesis of arecoline hydrobromide (**6**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] N.B. compound #4 is similar to a compound used in the synthesis of GSK1360707F.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Fischer esterification of nicotinic acid (niacin) (**1**) gives methyl nicotinate (**2**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Alkylation with methyl iodide then gives 3-methoxycarbonyl-1-methylpyridinium iodide (**3**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Hydride reduction with an agent such as potassium borohydride thus gives the tetrahydropyridine (**4**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Salt formation with HBr completes the synthesis (**5**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] A double Mannich reaction between methylamine (**1**), acetaldehyde (**2**) and formaldehyde (**3**) in the presence of hydroxylamine hydrochloride is supposed to have delivered 1-methyl-1,2,5,6-tetrahydropyridine-3-carbaldehyde oxime hydrochloride (**4**) as the product.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Dehydration of the aldoxime to the nitrile occurs upon treatment with acetic anhydride giving 3-cyano-1-methyl-1,2,5,6-tetrahydropyridine (**5**).
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Functional group interconversion of the nitrile to the methyl carboxylate ester then occurs upon acid-catalyzed treatment in methanol, and then conversion to the HBr salt completes the synthesis.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Although the first step is not very high yielding, if one substitutes methoxyamine for hydroxylamine procedure could be used for a one-pot synthesis of milameline.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline is used in the synthesis of a variety of other drugs, including paroxetine, femoxetine, nocaine, DMNPC, piquindone, PC10058081 (epiboxidine type), FT-0731096 [114724-56-0], piper-brasofensine piper-Tesofensine and BRN 0023391 [102206-67-7].
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Analogues of and related compounds to arecoline include arecaidine, guavacoline, guvacine, nipecotic acid, nicotinic acid, muscarine, SKF-89976A, tiagabine, and CI-966.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Xanomeline, the anti-schizophrenia component in the approved drug xanomeline/trospium chloride, also has structural similarities to arecoline.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Owing to its muscarinic and nicotinic agonist properties, arecoline has shown improvement in the learning ability of healthy volunteers.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Since one of the hallmarks of Alzheimer's disease is a cognitive decline, arecoline was suggested as a treatment to slow down this process.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Arecoline administered intravenously did indeed show modest verbal and spatial memory improvement in Alzheimer's patients, though due to arecoline's possible carcinogenic properties (see § Toxicity), it is not the first drug of choice for this degenerative disease.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Anecdotal reports indicate that it has a short-lived effect against schizophrenia.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] Among male schizophrenia patients, higher areca nut consumption is associated with weaker symptoms.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It inspired the development of xanomeline.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] It enhances learning and memory in rodents.
[src:arecoline/arecoline] In 2012, Chinese Ministry of Agriculture listed arecoline hydrobromide as an abolished veterinary drug and stopped its production and use.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The nocaine family includes a diverse assortment of piperidine based cocaine mimetics.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The parent compound nocaine was developed in an attempt to create a substitute drug for cocaine for the treatment of addiction, and was found to substitute for cocaine in animal models while having significantly less abuse potential.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Although Kozikowski reported compound with chlorine in 1998, plain phenyl was reported earlier than this by John Plati.
[src:arecoline/cpca] There are several novel ways to produce these compounds, but background stems from arecoline chemistry.
[src:arecoline/cpca] This is analogous to the phenyltropanes which use Methylecgonidine.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Paroxetine (*Paxil*) and femoxetine were also developed using arecoline conjugate additions of aromatic moieties.
[src:arecoline/cpca] These are serotonin based antidepressants though, whereas Kozikowski's team was the first to highlight activity at the DAT.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Further nocaine derivatives were developed for treating addiction from Kozikowski's teachings.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Smith specifically states that the butyrophenone analog of nocaine is an active agent, as well as specifying pthalimide type alkylamino agents.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The Ketanserin analog devised by Peter Meltzer uses an altogether different methodology of synthesis: The same procedure was employed years earlier for GSK1360707F, and was known from before this from RTI diaryltropanes.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Thus, these methods are now well known in the art and do not necessarily rely on the use of arecoline as a starting material.
[src:arecoline/cpca] One of the more promising methods of synthesis relies on a protocol that was taken for paroxetine.
[src:arecoline/cpca] This is known as the Czibula procedure and was patented. {Note: can't go directly from syn alcohols to syn ethers due to rearrangement and therefore need tosyl group.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Another protocol is the pigs liver enzyme (PLE) protocol.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The method of improving the cited Ki by 3',4'-dichlorophenyl is now well known in the art and is heavily patented.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Like cocaine, (−)-cis-CPCA and (+)-CPCA bind to the dopamine transporter and inhibit dopamine uptake, stimulate motor activity in rodents and completely substitute for cocaine in discrimination tests.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Pretreatment with (−)-cis-CPCA or (+)-CPCA enhances the cocaine discriminative stimulus in rats.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The generally lower efficacy of (+)-CPCA in locomotor and methamphetamine discrimination tests could result from the differential selectivity of the two isomers for the DAT relative to the SERT.
[src:arecoline/cpca] That is, if serotonin receptor activation is requisite for maximal efficacy, the difference SERT affinity between (−)-cis-CPCA and (+)-CPCA might play a contributory role in accounting for the differences in the observed pharmacology.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Catecholamine selective drugs, like TMP (methylphenidate), are reported to possess decent abuse potential though, so it is not easy to gauge why (+)-CPCA does not entice a strong self-administration propensity.
[src:arecoline/cpca] A possible explanation might be nocaine preferentially binds to the ↓ DAT, in which case it would be expected to behave somewhat differently from cocaine.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Some sort of cholinergic effect might also be aversive.
[src:arecoline/cpca] For example, muscarinic activity of benztropine analogs is known to limit their reinforcing potential.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Ion-channel activity is another factor that can be used to explain certain differences in pharmacology.
[src:arecoline/cpca] It is possible that sigma receptor activity might also account for some of the differences between cocaine and these piperidine mimics (R.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Sigma receptors are not specific to cocaine, other psychostimulants like methylphenidate, methamphetamine (E.
[src:arecoline/cpca] 2005), and phencyclidine are also linked to this neural target.
[src:arecoline/cpca] An increased understanding of this receptor recently led to a novel AD being reported that is based around its pharmacology.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In summary, (+)-CPCA has lower potency and efficacy than cocaine in increasing locomotor activity in rodents.
[src:arecoline/cpca] (+)-CPCA only manages to produce partial methamphetamine-like discriminative stimulus effects, although it is fully cocaine-like in cocaine-trained animals.
[src:arecoline/cpca] (+)-CPCA has lower reinforcing potential than cocaine as assessed by fixed and progressive ratio IV self-administration tests in rats, with its reinforcing effects confirmed by rhesus monkeys.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Furthermore, (+)-CPCA dose dependently antagonizes cocaine-induced locomotion and potentiates the discriminative stimulus effects of a low dose of cocaine.
[src:arecoline/cpca] (+)-CPCA, unlike cocaine, does not enhance cocaine-induced convulsions.
[src:arecoline/cpca] These results suggest that (+)-CPCA completely mimics certain behavioral actions of cocaine, whereas acting like a weak partial agonist in others, including its ability to attenuate cocaine-induced increase in locomotion and to serve as a positive reinforcing agent in rodents.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Thus, (+)-CPCA may have potential utility in the treatment of cocaine addiction, and also offer valuable pharmacological information, furthering our understanding of cocaine's mechanism of action, because it exhibits fundamental differences from other related DARI molecules.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The arecoline route goes the same as for RTI-31 starting from Methylecgonidine.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Trudell lays down the groundwork for the correct procedure that was then heavily patented by SKF.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The temperature for forming the Grignard reagent needs to be reflux whereas the temperature needs to be refrigerated for the conjugate addition.
[src:arecoline/cpca] A catalytic amount of CuCl can encourage soft over hard addition.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Quench conditions (things like strength of acid used, quench temperature and time of quench).
[src:arecoline/cpca] A series of novel N- and 3α-modified nocaine analogs were synthesized and tested for their SNDRI activity and behavioral properties in mice.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The rational design of ligands with a predetermined potency at and selectivity for monoamine transporters is hindered by the lack of knowledge about the 3D structure of these targets.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In cases where the 3D structure of the binding site in a target protein is not well defined, as is the case for the monoamine transporter proteins, one can perform ligand-based design to develop a pharmacophore.
[src:arecoline/cpca] That is, by studying the conformational properties of a series of pharmacologically similar compounds, one can form hypotheses regarding the pharmacophore.
[src:arecoline/cpca] This model was successfully used for the design of a novel piperidine-based DAT inhibitor, that is economically affordable to manufacture.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Although the in vivo metabolism of (+)-CPCA is also likely to involve N-demethylation, metabolism to the corresponding free acid, to give a compound inactive at all monoamine transporters, will probably be the predominant pathway *in vivo*.
[src:arecoline/cpca] It was reasoned that metabolism via esterase action can be avoided by replacing the ester group with a bioisosteric group that is more stable to metabolic degradation.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In previous studies, it was found that oxadiazole, although cocaine-like in activity, exhibits a significantly longer duration of action due to slower rate of metabolism.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In general, relative to the corresponding N-methyl compounds, the norpiperidines exhibited an increased activity at the SERT/NET and only modest changes at the DAT.
[src:arecoline/cpca] An interesting difference between cocaine, ester **1a**, alcohol **2a**, and norester **1b** is that the latter two compounds are substantially longer acting than cocaine in locomotor activity tests in mice.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Another result of N-demethylation is an initial depressant action of **1b** followed by delayed locomotor stimulation, which might be due to interaction with GABA receptors or mGlu5.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In an earlier study, it was found that 3α-amido and bulky 3α-oxadiazoyl nocaine ligands, which possess greater stability relative to the ester functional group, and are therefore more attractive as potential therapies, are inactive.
[src:arecoline/cpca] This result led to the hypothesis that the binding site of the DAT and NET in close proximity to the 3α-position of the piperidine ring is compact and cannot accommodate bulky, sterically occluded substituents, like the 3-substituted 1,2,4-oxadiazolyl groups.
[src:arecoline/cpca] It was reasoned that introduction of a methylene spacer would confer improved monoamine transporter binding affinity upon the resultant molecules.
[src:arecoline/cpca] One of the possible reasons that the C2–C3 compounds are more active than the C1 compounds is that the polar group present in the more flexible 3α-appendage of the C2–C3 ligands is able to avoid unfavorable interactions with the binding site in close proximity to the piperidine ring.
[src:arecoline/cpca] For the same reason the appendage in the C2–C3 series may more closely, but not precisely, mimic the binding mode of the more active *SS* based ligands, and possibly even transfer over to tropane based compounds.
[src:arecoline/cpca] To better understand the difference between the C1 and the C2–C3 series, the compounds were energy minimized and flexibly superimposed on WIN-35,428.
[src:arecoline/cpca] The resulting overlay shows that only the C2–C3 ligands are able to adopt a conformation in which the polar group of the 3α-substituent occupies the position proximal to that of the 2β-polar group in WIN35428.
[src:arecoline/cpca] A generally recognized pharmacophore model for cocaine and phenyltropanes comprises two electrostatic interactions of the basic nitrogen and the ester group of the C-2 substituent, and one hydrophobic interaction of the C-3 aryl group.
[src:arecoline/cpca] This model has been disputed because of the finding that in certain compounds neither the basic N nor the ester group was necessary for high binding affinity and inhibition of MAR.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Instead, a hydrophobic pocket was proposed to exist in the vicinity of the C-2 carbon.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Carroll et al., however, provided further evidence for an electrostatic interaction at the C-2β-position in a later study.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Other models proposed for the DAT binding site include a linear fashion binding pocket for the 3β-substituted phenyltropane analogs, and a prohibited conical region about 5.5–10 Å distant from the 3α-substituted piperidine ring.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Noticeably, high potency at the DAT of dimeric piperidine-based esters and amides suggested that the flexible linker combining the two piperidine units was able to adjust its orientation and to avoid unfavorable interactions with the binding site.
[src:arecoline/cpca] All these lines of evidence suggest that the DAT binding site is much more complicated than the proposed pharmacophore models.
[src:arecoline/cpca] In an attempt to uncover the details of the DAT binding site, a number of 3D-QSAR studies were performed.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Several QSAR/CoMFA studies focused on phenyltropanes concluded that an increased negative electrostatic potential in the regions around the 3β-substituent of the tropane ring and the para-position of the phenyl ring favored high potency in inhibiting the MATs.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Wright et al. studied the role of the 3β-substituent of tropanes in binding to the DAT and blocking DA re-uptake.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Their CoMFA model indicated that the 3β-substituent binding site is **barrel-shaped** and hydrophobic interactions make a dominant contribution to the binding, which is consistent with the studies of 3α-substituted tropane analogs reported by Newman et al.
[src:arecoline/cpca] Newman and co-authors also studied N-substituted tropanes and concluded that the steric interaction of the N-substituent with the DAT is a principal factor for the binding affinity.
